article.headline: Kansas 74, Oklahoma State 61
article.story:
LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) -- Crystal Kemp had a season-high 24 points
and five rebounds to lead Kansas over Oklahoma State 74-61 Saturday
night, giving interim coach Lynette Woodard her first coaching
victory.

Woodard was appointed interim coach Thursday after Marian
Washington decided to take a medical leave of absence. Saturday
night's game was the first time Washington has missed a game in her
31 seasons of coaching the Jayhawks.

Oklahoma State cut the lead to 60-51 in the second half but
Kansas (9-9, 2-5 Big 12) went on a 10-2 run to give the Jayhawks a
70-53 lead and the Cowgirls (8-11, 3-5) couldn't get any closer.

Aquanita Burrass added 14 points, with Lauren Ervin and Erica
Hallman both finishing with 13 points.

Trisha Skibbe had 21 points and five rebounds to lead Oklahoma
State. Eliz Gomes added 11 points.

Kemp scored 10 points during a 13-4 run early in the game to
give Kansas a 23-14 lead in the first half. The Cowgirls cut the
lead to 27-23 but Kansas closed the half on a 13-4 run and led
40-27 at halftime.

Woodard has spent five seasons as an assistant under Washington.
She played for Kansas from 1978 to 1981, was a four-time Kodak
All-American in college and played basketball overseas before
playing in the WNBA for two seasons. In 1985, Woodard became the
first woman to ever play for the Harlem Globetrotters.
